# Git Workflow & Commits

## Core Behavior
* NEVER run `git commit` unless explicitly asked.
* After making changes, always wait for review and explicit approval before committing.

## Git Commit Philosophy
Git commits are documentation snapshots capturing *why* decisions were made at that point in time. Reasoning that would be dangerous in code comments (which go stale) belongs here. Reader should understand the thought process without overexplanation.

## Format Structure
<label>: <lowercase tldr>

* <Properly cased main point>
  - Technical sub-detail
  - Another sub-detail
* <Another main point>
  - Sub-detail

## Formatting Rules
* Subject line: 50 chars ideal, 72 max.
* Body lines: 72 chars max (wrap and indent as needed).
* NO empty lines between bullet points.
* Label: domain/component (e.g., "telemetry", "ui", "api") or commit type (e.g., "bug", "feat") if more relevant.
* TLDR: concise, lowercase.
* Main bullets: asterisks (*) with proper casing.
* Sub-bullets: dashes (-), indented 2 spaces.
* Prioritize concise and easy-to-read text over strict grammatical correctness.
* Not too technical - make it easy to understand.
* Always include WHY decisions were made.
* Don't overexplain - just enough context.

## Example
telemetry: add metrics support for client apps

* Add recordGauge and recordCounter AIDL methods for client
  metric submission
  - Gauges track current state, counters track cumulative values
  - Different semantics require different handling
* Register metrics lazily on first client submission
  - Clients send metrics dynamically without coordination
  - Single metric name supports multiple time series via
    attributes
* Filter stale gauge values (>5min) for graceful degradation
  - Keeps exporting last value rather than dropping metric
  - Prevents dashboard gaps when clients disconnect
